 ). The temperament of individual mammals, a heritable trait among artiodactyls (
 Murphy 
  et al., 1994
 ), plays an important role in how situations are experienced (
 Beausoleil 
  et al., 2008
 ). For example, individual roe deer (
 Capreolus capreolus) manifest different responses to stress (
 Monestier 
  et al., 2016
 ) and therefore, presumably, different levels of sympathetic activation. Individual variability in sympathetic responses to the same stressor may contribute to an underlying plasticity in the control of selective brain cooling (
